1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,080
Ok, let's start right away and dive into this new analysis.

2
00:00:04,080 --> 00:00:08,759
Today we explore a fascinating topic, which, as the title on the screen says,

3
00:00:08,759 --> 00:00:11,599
is called the curse of state resources.

4
00:00:11,599 --> 00:00:16,679
And I want to immediately challenge, from the very first seconds, an idea that we all take for granted.

5
00:00:16,679 --> 00:00:21,000
The belief that a sudden shower of public money on a local administration

6
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:23,960
automatically brings enormous benefits to society.

7
00:00:23,960 --> 00:00:26,879
Usually when extra funds arrive, people celebrate, right?

8
00:00:26,919 --> 00:00:31,799
Well, hold on tight because economic research tells us that the story is very, very different.

9
00:00:31,799 --> 00:00:33,640
It's super intuitive, right?

10
00:00:33,640 --> 00:00:39,560
It comes naturally to think that injecting a sea of money into a municipality magically solves structural problems.

11
00:00:39,560 --> 00:00:44,519
More budget, great, let's build more schools and repair roads, hire doctors.

12
00:00:44,519 --> 00:00:46,159
It seems like the perfect equation.

13
00:00:46,159 --> 00:00:50,359
But the reality emerging from empirical data is incredibly paradoxical.

14
00:00:50,359 --> 00:00:54,200
Economic literature shows us that if the right controls are missing,

15
00:00:54,200 --> 00:01:00,720
this sudden abundance of resources can literally crumble the foundations of local democratic institutions.

16
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:04,280
And this is where a truly counterintuitive concept comes into play,

17
00:01:04,280 --> 00:01:06,040
uncovered by a team of economists,

18
00:01:06,040 --> 00:01:08,560
Brollo, Nannicini, Perotti, and Tabellini,

19
00:01:08,560 --> 00:01:11,879
who coined the term political resource curse.

20
00:01:11,879 --> 00:01:13,280
In practice, what do they tell us?

21
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:17,400
They tell us that when a local government receives a lot of money that doesn't come

22
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:20,920
from the direct taxes of its own citizens, a disaster happens.

23
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:24,320
The quality of those who govern unexpectedly begins to collapse,

24
00:01:24,320 --> 00:01:26,439
a real short circuit.

25
00:01:26,439 --> 00:01:31,359
Let's move on to Section 1, the theory of moral hazard.

26
00:01:31,359 --> 00:01:37,400
Let's see exactly why more money can paradoxically mean more problems.

27
00:01:37,400 --> 00:01:38,599
Think about it for a moment.

28
00:01:38,599 --> 00:01:42,400
The mechanism is as simple as it is fascinating.

29
00:01:42,400 --> 00:01:46,200
Imagine that your municipality's budget suddenly explodes.

30
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:50,520
We citizens see some construction sites arrive, two or three extra services,

31
00:01:50,599 --> 00:01:51,799
and we lower our guard.

32
00:01:51,799 --> 00:01:55,239
We become less demanding, and do you know what happens then?

33
00:01:55,239 --> 00:01:59,519
The politician in charge suddenly has much more room to embezzle money

34
00:01:59,519 --> 00:02:03,959
or create political rents without anyone noticing or making too much of a fuss.

35
00:02:03,959 --> 00:02:05,119
And there's worse.

36
00:02:05,119 --> 00:02:09,560
A pile of easy money acts like a magnet for opportunistic candidates,

37
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:14,680
perhaps less prepared, who only aim for easy gain and not the public good.

38
00:02:14,680 --> 00:02:17,240
Section 2, the perfect laboratory,

39
00:02:17,240 --> 00:02:20,879
Brazilian municipalities and FPM transfers.

40
00:02:20,879 --> 00:02:25,520
To prove this theory beyond a shadow of a doubt, researchers needed real data,

41
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:27,439
not just formulas on a blackboard,

42
00:02:27,439 --> 00:02:29,920
and they found the perfect laboratory in Brazil,

43
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:34,360
studying the Fundo de Participação dos Municípios or FPM.

44
00:02:34,360 --> 00:02:37,480
It's a very rigid system that distributes federal money to municipalities

45
00:02:37,480 --> 00:02:39,680
based on population brackets.

46
00:02:39,680 --> 00:02:42,000
In practice, invisible lines are created,

47
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,640
you just need to exceed the threshold by a few inhabitants and boom, a massive

48
00:02:45,640 --> 00:02:47,480
sudden jump in funding occurs.

49
00:02:47,480 --> 00:02:52,400
And this creates an incredible situation, the classic regression discontinuity design.

50
00:02:52,400 --> 00:02:55,160
Imagine two nearby cities, practically twins.

51
00:02:55,160 --> 00:03:00,080
City A has 10,188 inhabitants and receives normal funding.

52
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:02,880
City B has 10,189.

53
00:03:02,880 --> 00:03:05,120
For just one single extra inhabitant,

54
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:09,720
City B crosses the magic threshold and gets a flood of money from the central government.

55
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:11,040
It's completely arbitrary,

56
00:03:11,040 --> 00:03:13,920
but it allows researchers to compare two identical realities

57
00:03:13,920 --> 00:03:17,880
where the only true difference is how full the state wallet is.

58
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:21,440
We come to Section 3, more money, more corruption.

59
00:03:21,440 --> 00:03:26,480
And here we analyze the burning evidence that emerged from the Brazilian anti-corruption program.

60
00:03:26,480 --> 00:03:31,320
In 2003, Brazil launched an independent program that randomly selects municipalities

61
00:03:31,320 --> 00:03:34,800
and sends relentless auditors to comb through the accounts.

62
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:36,720
And the reports are shocking.

63
00:03:36,720 --> 00:03:39,520
They documented an explosion of criminal creativity.

64
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:41,240
Blatantly rigged tenders,

65
00:03:41,240 --> 00:03:44,000
goods purchased at absurdly inflated prices,

66
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:45,880
money diverted to private accounts

67
00:03:45,880 --> 00:03:48,879
and even reimbursements for literally phantom expenses.

68
00:03:48,879 --> 00:03:50,439
In short, a disaster.

69
00:03:50,439 --> 00:03:51,680
But the real question is,

70
00:03:51,680 --> 00:03:55,920
is there a link between these frauds and the funding jumps we talked about earlier?

71
00:03:55,920 --> 00:03:58,439
The answer is absolutely yes.

72
00:03:58,439 --> 00:04:01,120
Let's look at the raw data, because it speaks very clearly.

73
00:04:01,120 --> 00:04:04,080
A 10% increase in federal transfers

74
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:08,760
causes the incidence of general corruption to jump by 4.7%.

75
00:04:08,760 --> 00:04:11,320
It's not a margin of error; it's a huge figure.

76
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:13,280
This means that the shower of money,

77
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:15,760
instead of calming and improving the administration,

78
00:04:15,760 --> 00:04:18,920
acted as a real doping for illegal practices.

79
00:04:18,920 --> 00:04:21,879
And hold on tight, because there's worse.

80
00:04:21,879 --> 00:04:24,960
If we exclude cases of simple, albeit serious,

81
00:04:24,960 --> 00:04:26,480
poor administration,

82
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:31,240
and focus only on the overwhelming evidence of serious and blatant corruption,

83
00:04:31,240 --> 00:04:33,920
the jump is even more sensational.

84
00:04:33,920 --> 00:04:37,920
Episodes of blatant theft jump by 7.3%,

85
00:04:37,920 --> 00:04:41,480
against the usual 10% budget increase.

86
00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:44,600
It is the crushing proof that moral hazard materializes

87
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:48,040
at the exact moment when the coffers are filled for free.

88
00:04:48,040 --> 00:04:52,720
And here comes the final blow to our trust in the electoral system.

89
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:56,360
You would expect a mayor caught with his hands in the cookie jar

90
00:04:56,360 --> 00:04:59,800
to lose the elections disastrously, right? Wrong.

91
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:04,400
The data tells us that if a city is suddenly flooded with federal funds,

92
00:05:04,400 --> 00:05:06,439
citizens tend to turn a blind eye.

93
00:05:06,439 --> 00:05:08,839
The extra money cushions the scandal,

94
00:05:08,839 --> 00:05:13,839
and the electoral punishment for corrupt behavior becomes incredibly weaker.

95
00:05:13,839 --> 00:05:15,160
Absurd, right.

96
00:05:15,160 --> 00:05:18,439
Section 4. Flight of political talent

97
00:05:18,439 --> 00:05:21,519
leading to the decline in candidate quality.

98
00:05:21,519 --> 00:05:24,839
The resource curse doesn't just bring corruption,

99
00:05:24,839 --> 00:05:27,120
it also creates a scorched earth for talent.

100
00:05:27,120 --> 00:05:28,680
Look at the election data,

101
00:05:28,680 --> 00:05:32,680
as funds increase, the most educated people flee from politics.

102
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:35,079
With 10% more easy money,

103
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:39,199
the share of challengers with a degree drops by 2.7%.

104
00:05:39,199 --> 00:05:41,479
Those with skills go to the private sector,

105
00:05:41,479 --> 00:05:43,199
tired of an opaque system,

106
00:05:43,199 --> 00:05:44,719
and do you know who benefits?

107
00:05:44,719 --> 00:05:46,120
The incumbent mayor,

108
00:05:46,120 --> 00:05:48,839
maybe the very one managing funds in a murky way,

109
00:05:48,839 --> 00:05:54,519
who sees his chances of being re-elected increase by 4% thanks to the lack of real rivals.

110
00:05:54,519 --> 00:05:56,360
And we come to Section 5,

111
00:05:56,360 --> 00:05:58,079
the price of democracy,

112
00:05:58,079 --> 00:06:01,479
evaluating the true cost of sudden state revenues.

113
00:06:01,520 --> 00:06:06,600
It is all perfectly summarized in this quote from the study's authors.

114
00:06:06,600 --> 00:06:10,360
Pouring boatloads of money from above onto a municipality,

115
00:06:10,360 --> 00:06:13,680
without rigorous supervision, is not development.

116
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:15,600
It is a tragic paradox.

117
00:06:15,600 --> 00:06:20,160
Easy money attracts vultures seeking personal enrichment,

118
00:06:20,160 --> 00:06:24,800
and alienates those who actually have the tools and skills to improve society.

119
00:06:24,800 --> 00:06:28,040
It is a destructive dynamic for civic virtue.

120
00:06:28,040 --> 00:06:30,720
And this brings us to our final reflection.

121
00:06:30,720 --> 00:06:36,320
Often, in the news, we take pleasure in how many millions have been unlocked for this or that region.

122
00:06:36,320 --> 00:06:39,480
But the real question, the provocative one we must ask ourselves,

123
00:06:39,480 --> 00:06:42,720
is whether we are blindly celebrating the number of zeros on the check

124
00:06:42,720 --> 00:06:47,480
or demanding a system that guarantees the integrity of those who will spend that money,

125
00:06:47,480 --> 00:06:50,960
because as we saw today, without transparency and without rigor,

126
00:06:50,960 --> 00:06:55,200
the greatest financial blessing can literally transform in an instant

127
00:06:55,200 --> 00:06:57,280
into the most lethal of curses.